m":"Staunton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Staunton, Newark, Nottinghamshire, England":"Staunton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1000–":"circa 1000–Overleden","1005–1080":"1005–1080","1027–1076":"1027–1076","1000–Male":"1000–Overleden","1080":"1080","1027":"1027","1005":"1005","1026":"1026","about 1025":"circa 1025","1000":"1000","1076":"1076","about 1000":"circa 1000","Knighton, Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Staunton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Staunton, Nottinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Staunton, Newark, Nottinghamshire, England":"Staunton, Nottinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1000–":"about 1000–Deceased","1005–1080":"1005–1080","1027–1076":"1027–1076","1000–Male":"1000–Deceased","1080":"1080","1027":"1027","1005":"1005","1026":"1026","about 1025":"about 1025","1000":"1000","1076":"1076","about 1000":"about 1000","Knighton, Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Staunton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Staunton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Staunton, Newark, Nottinghamshire, England":"Staunton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Staunton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Caitlin, Ciaran, Cormac.","English and Irish: variant of   Stanton  . This English name has been established (in this spelling) since medieval times in Ireland (Mayo, Connacht), where it has been Gaelicized as <b>de Stonndún</b>. Compare   McEvilly  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McEvilly","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Eamonn.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac an Mhílidh</b> ‘son of the knight’, from Gaelic <i>míleadh</i> ‘warrior, knight’. In County Mayo and County Cork, a family of English origin Gaelicized their name from   Staunton   to <i>Mac an Mhílidh</i>, apparently because of the latter's presumed similarity to the name of their ancestor, <i>Milo</i> de Stanton."]},{"name":"Stanton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places in England called Stanton or Staunton, especially Stanton in Staffordshire and Staunton in Worcestershire, all named with Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Most of the placenames come from their situation on stony ground, but in the case of Stanton Harcourt in Oxfordshire and Stanton Drew in Avon the reference is to the proximity of prehistoric stone monuments. The name has also sometimes been chosen by Ashkenazic Jews as an Americanized form of various like-sounding Jewish surnames. This surname has also long been established in Ireland (especially Mayo)."]}]},{"name":"Mauger","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and Channel Islands (Guernsey and Jersey): from the Old French (Norman) personal name <i>Maug(i)er</i>, <i>Malg(i)er</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Madalgar(i)</i>, <i>Malger</i>, composed of the elements <i>madal</i> ‘council, meeting’ and <i>gar(i)</i> ‘spear’, or from <i>Amalgar(i)</i>, with the first element <i>amal</i> ‘capable, brave, eager’. Compare   Major  ,   Monger  , and   Munger  .","Probably also an altered form of German   Mager  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Maugeri","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Carmine, Ignazio, Salvatore, Angelo, Camillo, Giuseppe, Orazio, Pietro.","Italian (southern):","variant of <b>Malgeri</b>, from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Madalgari</i> or <i>Amalgari</i> (see   Mauger  )."]},{"name":"Major","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the personal name <i>Malg(i)er</i>, <i>Maug(i)er</i>, an Old French form of ancient Germanic <i>Madalgar(i)</i> (see   Mauger  ).","Hungarian: from a shortened form of <i>majorosgazda</i> (see   Majoros  ) or a derivative of German   Meyer  .","Polish, Czech, and Slovak: from the military rank <i>major</i> (derived from Latin <i>maior</i> ‘greater’), a word related to English <i>mayor</i> and the German surname   Meyer  ."]},{"name":"Mangieri","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Gaspar, Mario, Angelo, Arsenio, Mafalda, Orazio, Rocco, Silvio.","Italian: variant of <b>Malgeri</b>, from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Madalgari</i> or <i>Amalgari</i> (see   Mauger  )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mauger De Staunton was born about 1000, in Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Anne De Staunton in 1026, in Staunton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1000–":"umbes 1000–Surnud","1005–1080":"1005–1080","1027–1076":"1027–1076","1000–Male":"1000–Surnud","1080":"1080","1027":"1027","1005":"1005","1026":"1026","about 1025":"umbes 1025","1000":"1000","1076":"1076","about 1000":"umbes 1000","Knighton, Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Staunton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Staunton, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Staunton, Newark, Nottinghamshire, England":"Staunton, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1000–":"noin 1000–Kuollut","1005–1080":"1005–1080","1027–